242
00:15:35,852 --> 00:15:38,880
Professor Weldon holds the Bainbridge Chair
in Comparative Literature

243
00:15:38,980 --> 00:15:41,382
and she's about to publish
what will prove to be

244
00:15:41,482 --> 00:15:43,509
the definitive work on Jane Austen.

245
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:45,131
Oh, I'm so sorry. (CHUCKLES)

246
00:15:45,695 --> 00:15:46,929
You don't like Jane Austen?

247
00:15:47,029 --> 00:15:48,389
No, no, she's obviously brilliant.

248
00:15:48,489 --> 00:15:51,726
It's just I find it all
a bit trivial, you know?

249
00:15:51,826 --> 00:15:54,354
Really? That's fascinating. How so?

250
00:15:54,454 --> 00:15:57,523
Well, isn't it all, you know,
"Who's going to the ball tonight?

251
00:15:57,623 --> 00:15:59,817
"My corset is askew.
However will I curtsey?"

252
00:15:59,917 --> 00:16:01,018
(ALL LAUGHING)

253
00:16:02,044 --> 00:16:03,279
I'd also like you to meet...

254
00:16:03,379 --> 00:16:05,406
In other words, why should
a 21st century man care

255
00:16:05,506 --> 00:16:07,658
about the obstacles facing
a 19th century woman?

256
00:16:07,758 --> 00:16:10,745
No, that makes me sound like a misogynist.
I love and respect women.

257
00:16:10,845 --> 00:16:12,121
As long as they're not writing.

258
00:16:12,221 --> 00:16:14,995
On the contrary, there are
myriad women writers I adore.

259
00:16:15,725 --> 00:16:17,873
- Can you name one?
- Elaine May.

260
00:16:18,853 --> 00:16:20,171
I'm not familiar with her work.

261
00:16:20,271 --> 00:16:24,547
Oh, she wrote A New Leaf, The Birdcage,
she did an uncredited rewrite on Tootsie.

262
00:16:26,319 --> 00:16:28,388
- Movies?
- Mmm-hmm.

263
00:16:28,488 --> 00:16:30,681
We're talking about literature.

264
00:16:30,781 --> 00:16:33,810
And while you may not think much
of the women writers of that period,

265
00:16:33,910 --> 00:16:36,020
Austen, Woolf, and the Bronte sisters
were artists

266
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:39,065
who represented
the female empowerment of their age.

267
00:16:39,165 --> 00:16:40,441
Oh, well, forgive me,

268
00:16:40,541 --> 00:16:42,985
but I'm just a little bit tired
of "female empowerment."

269
00:16:43,085 --> 00:16:45,279
Whoa! Battle stations.

270
00:16:46,339 --> 00:16:48,324
Dr Lerner, you must
have an opinion on this?

271
00:16:48,424 --> 00:16:51,994
(LAUGHS) I have a wife and
four daughters. I have no opinions.

272
00:16:52,094 --> 00:16:54,997
What exactly is
your opinion, Mr Michaels?

273
00:16:55,097 --> 00:16:57,708
- Another glass?
- Thank you so much, that's nice.

274
00:16:57,808 --> 00:17:01,587
It's just, honestly, everything seems to be
about female empowerment nowadays.

275
00:17:01,687 --> 00:17:03,965
You know, any meeting I go
to in Hollywood, someone says,

276
00:17:04,065 --> 00:17:06,926
"You know what we need? A kick-ass girl.
That would be a great twist."

277
00:17:07,026 --> 00:17:08,845
Except every movie has a kick-ass girl.

278
00:17:08,945 --> 00:17:11,931
You know, some martial-arts,
CGI, slow-motion woman

279
00:17:12,031 --> 00:17:14,642
who kicks the crap out of
every man in her path.

280
00:17:14,742 --> 00:17:17,645
Can I tell you what would be
truly innovative?

281
00:17:17,745 --> 00:17:19,772
A movie without a kick-ass girl.

282
00:17:19,872 --> 00:17:23,272
Or, better yet, a movie where
a woman gets her ass kicked.

283
00:17:28,548 --> 00:17:30,241
Perhaps you'd like to kick mine.

284
00:17:30,633 --> 00:17:33,532
No, don't be silly.
I didn't mean literally.

285
00:17:34,637 --> 00:17:36,614
Besides, not much of a target there.
(LAUGHS)

286
00:17:37,515 --> 00:17:39,750
- Which I mean in a very nice way...
- (GASPS)

287
00:17:39,850 --> 00:17:41,293
Cos you are in great shape.

288
00:17:41,602 --> 00:17:43,045
You're... You're svelte.

289
00:17:43,145 --> 00:17:44,213
Uh, this... Uh...

290
00:17:44,313 --> 00:17:46,381
I'm sure you'd like to meet, uh...

291
00:17:48,150 --> 00:17:49,251
Somebody.

292
00:17:59,787 --> 00:18:03,107
JIM:
Hey. So this worked out great, right?

293
00:18:03,874 --> 00:18:05,693
Two of us living right
next door to each other.

294
00:18:05,793 --> 00:18:07,612
- KEITH: Yeah.
- I'll give you a lift in tomorrow.

295
00:18:07,712 --> 00:18:08,696
Oh, thank you, Jim.

296
00:18:08,796 --> 00:18:11,407
You know, you're a lovely man
with an unusual dog...

297
00:18:11,507 --> 00:18:13,326
But I don't think I can do this.

298
00:18:13,426 --> 00:18:16,200
I actually miss LA,
and I didn't think that was possible.

299
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:19,290
"O thou invisible spirit of wine,

300
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:22,334
"if thou hast no name to be
known by, let us call thee devil!"

301
00:18:24,645 --> 00:18:25,755
When I was younger,

302
00:18:25,855 --> 00:18:28,299
I thought having the perfect
Shakespeare quote for any situation

303
00:18:28,399 --> 00:18:29,625
would make me beloved.

304
00:18:29,775 --> 00:18:31,302
It's surprisingly unhelpful.

305
00:18:31,402 --> 00:18:32,970
Yeah, it seems to really annoy people.

306
00:18:33,070 --> 00:18:35,798
- (MOBILE RINGING)
- Sorry, hang on, hang on, hang on.

307
00:18:39,410 --> 00:18:42,146
I'm going to have to take this.
I think I can find my house from here.

308
00:18:42,246 --> 00:18:44,148
OK, sure, you go for it.

309
00:18:44,248 --> 00:18:46,025
- Listen though...
- Hang on one second.

310
00:18:46,125 --> 00:18:49,820
Give teaching a shot, OK?
It gets its hooks in you, you'll see.

311
00:18:49,920 --> 00:18:51,239
With all respect, I don't believe

312
00:18:51,339 --> 00:18:53,533
that anything worth knowing
can be taught in a classroom.

313
00:18:53,633 --> 00:18:57,286
And I intend to do as little as possible
while carrying on with this charade.

314
00:18:57,386 --> 00:19:00,160
Yeah, if I gave it any thought,
I'd probably feel the same way.

315
00:19:00,514 --> 00:19:01,457
Yeah, hi.

316
00:19:01,557 --> 00:19:04,001
Oh, hi. I'm stuck in traffic,
I thought I'd check in. How's it going?

317
00:19:04,101 --> 00:19:07,129
I'm very, very, very,
very cold, and, uh,

318
00:19:07,229 --> 00:19:09,131
I have to read a huge box of scripts,

319
00:19:09,231 --> 00:19:12,843
and I just got into a fight with
Professor McGonagall about Jane Austen.

320
00:19:12,943 --> 00:19:15,346
You know, it's interesting
that you should bring that up.

321
00:19:15,446 --> 00:19:17,265
You know what J.K. Rowling said?

322
00:19:17,365 --> 00:19:19,308
"Where did I put
that last billion dollars?"

323
00:19:20,076 --> 00:19:22,353
She said that failure was the best
thing that ever happened to her

324
00:19:22,453 --> 00:19:24,146
cos it freed her from the inessential.

325
00:19:24,246 --> 00:19:28,234
It allowed her to concentrate on the
thing that mattered most. Writing.

326
00:19:28,334 --> 00:19:31,487
Maybe the time has come for me to write
that sequel to Paradise Misplaced

327
00:19:31,587 --> 00:19:33,781
that you've been hounding me
for all these years.

328
00:19:33,881 --> 00:19:35,491
Hey, hey. I thought
you weren't interested.

329
00:19:35,591 --> 00:19:38,160
You said the story was over,
and if I remember correctly,

330
00:19:38,260 --> 00:19:40,538
continuing it would be creative suicide.

331
00:19:40,638 --> 00:19:43,332
Yeah, well, that was when I was young
and believed in myself.

332
00:19:43,432 --> 00:19:45,159
So now is the perfect time.

333
00:20:27,268 --> 00:20:29,917
"Flo Bai."

334
00:20:31,647 --> 00:20:36,469
Hello, Flo. Congratulations
and welcome to the screenwriting class.

335
00:20:39,447 --> 00:20:40,719
"Dave Fenman."

336
00:20:44,034 --> 00:20:47,479
You're a good-looking guy, Dave.
Get your own screenwriting class.

337
00:21:09,477 --> 00:21:10,624
Not even close.

338
00:21:41,675 --> 00:21:45,325
Hello. Good morning. I'm Keith Michaels.

339
00:21:46,847 --> 00:21:48,119
Oh, thank you.

340
00:21:48,474 --> 00:21:50,167
Thanks very much. Thanks, yeah.

341
00:21:51,727 --> 00:21:52,712
Thank you.

342
00:21:52,812 --> 00:21:54,255
Well, now, um...

343
00:21:54,814 --> 00:21:57,466
Since it will be easier for me
to evaluate your material

344
00:21:57,566 --> 00:21:58,801
if I read an entire script,

345
00:21:58,901 --> 00:22:00,636
and you've all turned in 30 pages

346
00:22:00,736 --> 00:22:02,763
and the average screenplay is 120,

347
00:22:02,863 --> 00:22:04,636
that leaves roughly 90 to go.

348
00:22:04,949 --> 00:22:07,977
So if you write three pages a day,
six days a week,

349
00:22:08,077 --> 00:22:09,478
you should all be done in about a month.

350
00:22:09,578 --> 00:22:10,679
Let's meet again then.

351
00:22:10,913 --> 00:22:13,015
Great. Looking forward to it.

352
00:22:25,344 --> 00:22:28,831
Hey. That's the way all classes
should be. Five minutes.

353
00:22:28,931 --> 00:22:31,500
I had no intention of going that long,
I am so sorry.

354
00:22:31,600 --> 00:22:33,669
(LAUGHS) So maybe later,
do you want to catch up...

355
00:22:33,769 --> 00:22:36,005
Excuse me. Hi. Do you have a minute?

356
00:22:36,105 --> 00:22:37,798
Ah. Holly.

357
00:22:38,107 --> 00:22:40,801
Oh, yes. I work at the Campus Bookstore.

358
00:22:40,901 --> 00:22:42,002
(KEITH LAUGHS)

359
00:22:43,320 --> 00:22:45,723
Uh, so, Holly, this is Karen.

360
00:22:45,823 --> 00:22:48,184
- Yeah, we've taken some classes together.
- Hi.

361
00:22:48,284 --> 00:22:49,894
So you didn't accept my screenplay

362
00:22:49,994 --> 00:22:52,605
but I was wondering if you could give me
some constructive criticism.

363
00:22:52,705 --> 00:22:54,352
I thought that
I could come during office hours.

364
00:22:54,623 --> 00:22:55,649
Yes. Yes.

365
00:22:55,749 --> 00:22:58,443
- I'll see you later, Mr Michaels.
- Oh, Karen.

366
00:23:00,880 --> 00:23:01,864
(SNAPPING FINGERS)

367
00:23:01,964 --> 00:23:03,199
Hi. I'm still here.

368
00:23:03,299 --> 00:23:04,784
Yes. Yes, you are.

369
00:23:04,884 --> 00:23:06,577
Well the thing is, Holly...

370
00:23:06,677 --> 00:23:10,831
I'm not entirely sure that I have anything
very helpful to say regarding your screenplay.

371
00:23:10,931 --> 00:23:12,958
- Oh. That bad, huh?
- No, not at all.

372
00:23:13,058 --> 00:23:15,669
It's just that I don't really believe
that writing can be taught.

373
00:23:15,769 --> 00:23:18,631
Oh, interesting position
for a creative writing teacher to take.

374
00:23:18,731 --> 00:23:20,591
But true. You know,
you can't teach talent.

375
00:23:20,691 --> 00:23:22,051
I think most people have talent,

376
00:23:22,151 --> 00:23:23,761
they just haven't been exposed
to the right teachers.

377
00:23:23,861 --> 00:23:24,845
I beg to differ.

378
00:23:24,945 --> 00:23:26,722
You can get me the best music teacher
in the world

379
00:23:26,822 --> 00:23:28,808
and I still wouldn't be able to
write songs like Paul McCartney.

380
00:23:28,908 --> 00:23:29,975
How do you know? Have you tried?

381
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:31,060
No.

382
00:23:31,160 --> 00:23:33,513
- Do you want to write songs?
- Not at all.

383
00:23:33,913 --> 00:23:35,014
What are we talking about?

384
00:23:36,081 --> 00:23:40,778
About the fact that the most idiotic
thing that anyone has ever said

385
00:23:40,878 --> 00:23:43,280
is that if you just put your mind to it
and believe in yourself,

386
00:23:43,380 --> 00:23:45,032
there is nothing you can't accomplish.

387
00:23:45,132 --> 00:23:49,245
(LAUGHING)
I say that! Does that make me an idiot?

388
00:23:49,345 --> 00:23:51,368
No, no, not you. Other people.

389
00:23:59,355 --> 00:24:01,674
How can I make my script better?

390
00:24:02,775 --> 00:24:03,926
Uh...

391
00:24:04,026 --> 00:24:06,970
Right, well, it could be more...

392
00:24:07,696 --> 00:24:09,098
Um, organised.

393
00:24:09,198 --> 00:24:11,346
"More organised" how?

394
00:24:12,284 --> 00:24:14,352
- Uh, structurally.
- Structurally.

395
00:24:14,870 --> 00:24:16,017
Yep.

396
00:24:16,872 --> 00:24:18,565
Yeah. Structurally.

397
00:24:21,335 --> 00:24:23,445
Did you like that part
where she looks in the mirror

398
00:24:23,545 --> 00:24:25,114
and she sees herself as an old woman?

399
00:24:25,214 --> 00:24:27,575
Honestly, I found that
a little heavy-handed.

400
00:24:27,675 --> 00:24:30,578
(CLICKS TONGUE) So did I.
Which is why I didn't write it.

401
00:24:30,678 --> 00:24:32,955
You didn't read my screenplay, did you?

402
00:24:33,055 --> 00:24:36,083
No. But I didn't read anyone's screenplay,
don't take it personally.

403
00:24:36,183 --> 00:24:37,293
It's entirely personal.

404
00:24:37,393 --> 00:24:39,753
I worked on it and
I would like to tell this story.

405
00:24:39,853 --> 00:24:41,463
OK. You're in the class.

406
00:24:41,563 --> 00:24:44,086
No. I want you to read my script
and tell me if I have any potential.

407
00:24:45,150 --> 00:24:46,923
All right. I will read your screenplay.

408
00:24:47,194 --> 00:24:49,513
Thanks. I think.

409
00:24:50,906 --> 00:24:51,974
I'll let you eat in peace.

410
00:24:52,074 --> 00:24:54,723
Oh, thank you, thank you.
It's a bit late for that.

411
00:24:56,870 --> 00:24:58,472
(CLEARS THROAT)

412
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:02,017
Keith.

413
00:25:02,584 --> 00:25:03,856
Dr Lerner.

414
00:25:04,378 --> 00:25:06,238
Interesting wine
and cheese party last night.

415
00:25:06,338 --> 00:25:09,033
I am so sorry.
Honestly, I was nervous meeting everyone

416
00:25:09,133 --> 00:25:11,452
and you combine that
with the free-flowing wine

417
00:25:11,552 --> 00:25:13,871
and it is just a recipe
for Austen-bashing.

418
00:25:14,263 --> 00:25:16,540
Mary's a pretty powerful presence
around here, you know?

419
00:25:16,640 --> 00:25:18,583
She's tenured, she's published.

420
00:25:19,059 --> 00:25:21,036
She's also head of the Ethics Committee

421
00:25:21,353 --> 00:25:23,213
which means
she can make your life miserable.

422
00:25:23,313 --> 00:25:24,340
Mmm.

423
00:25:24,440 --> 00:25:25,587
Even get you fired.

424
00:25:26,316 --> 00:25:29,010
She wants me fired? Already?

425
00:25:29,319 --> 00:25:30,512
She's not happy.

426
00:25:30,612 --> 00:25:33,465
She did use words in her email
to me like "harassment".

427
00:25:34,199 --> 00:25:35,300
That's a very bad word.

428
00:25:35,576 --> 00:25:38,054
Yes, it is indeed. Here, walk with me.

429
00:25:38,787 --> 00:25:43,192
Listen, I know you're a big Hollywood guy,
obviously you don't need this job.

430
00:25:43,292 --> 00:25:45,986
Well, I wouldn't want to
let the students down, you know.

431
00:25:46,211 --> 00:25:49,986
Well, then I'm afraid you're going
to have to kiss her svelte ass.

432
00:25:50,591 --> 00:25:51,867
That sounds difficult.

433
00:25:51,967 --> 00:25:54,320
I couldn't do it.
And I was in Desert Storm.

434
00:25:55,220 --> 00:25:57,957
Should I bring her a gift
of appeasement, you know?

435
00:25:58,057 --> 00:25:59,329
What does she like?

436
00:25:59,641 --> 00:26:01,038
Jane Austen.

437
00:26:23,832 --> 00:26:25,855
(TYPING)

438
00:26:34,843 --> 00:26:38,322
FEMALE PRESENTER: And the award
for Best Original Screenplay goes to...

439
00:26:39,431 --> 00:26:42,459
Keith Michaels for Paradise Misplaced.

440
00:26:42,559 --> 00:26:43,752
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

441
00:26:43,852 --> 00:26:44,953
KEITH: Uh...

442
00:26:46,063 --> 00:26:47,164
This is, uh...

443
00:26:47,689 --> 00:26:51,176
Well, it's tragic
how much I'm enjoying getting this.

444
00:26:51,276 --> 00:26:52,798
(AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

445
00:26:54,154 --> 00:26:57,303
And it's with tremendous ill-grace, um,

446
00:26:58,033 --> 00:27:02,513
that I grudgingly acknowledge
the contribution of a few other people.

447
00:27:04,373 --> 00:27:09,320
Our brilliant director, Niles Kelling,
my very loud agent, Ellen Klein.

448
00:27:10,129 --> 00:27:13,608
My beautiful wife, Tina,
who, frankly, could do much better.

449
00:27:14,424 --> 00:27:18,037
And our son, Alex,
who I can honestly say

450
00:27:18,137 --> 00:27:21,040
is the only thing
I've ever had a hand in producing

451
00:27:21,140 --> 00:27:23,375
- not desperately in need of a rewrite.
- (AUDIENCE LAUGHING)

452
00:27:23,475 --> 00:27:26,503
So, uh, cheers, Alex, and go to bed.

453
00:27:26,603 --> 00:27:27,955
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

454
00:27:29,439 --> 00:27:30,586
Thank you.

455
00:27:34,736 --> 00:27:35,837
(VIDEO STOPS)

456
00:27:42,911 --> 00:27:44,103
(SNIFFS)

457
00:28:21,325 --> 00:28:25,145
I'm not interested in your feelings
about Persuasion, Miss Stein-Rosen,

458
00:28:25,245 --> 00:28:26,605
or anything else for that matter.

459
00:28:26,705 --> 00:28:29,858
I am interested in a
well-thought out analysis

460
00:28:29,958 --> 00:28:34,696
corroborated with evidence from the text
and only the text. Not Wikipedia.

461
00:28:34,796 --> 00:28:36,782
That's what I thought I was doing.

462
00:28:36,882 --> 00:28:38,325
What you thought
you were doing is irrelevant.

463
00:28:38,425 --> 00:28:42,905
What you have done or in this case,
not done, is what counts.

464
00:28:43,305 --> 00:28:44,998
Can I do some kind of extra credit?

465
00:28:45,098 --> 00:28:46,916
Like Habitat for Humanity?

466
00:28:47,100 --> 00:28:48,127
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

467
00:28:48,227 --> 00:28:49,328
Who is it?

468
00:28:52,272 --> 00:28:54,383
Hello. Uh, am I interrupting?

469
00:28:54,483 --> 00:28:56,510
I'm having office hours, Mr Michaels.

470
00:28:56,610 --> 00:28:57,886
Oh, OK.

471
00:28:57,986 --> 00:29:00,556
Hi, Mr Michaels.
I'm in your screenwriting class.

472
00:29:00,656 --> 00:29:01,890
Andrea Stein-Rosen.

473
00:29:01,990 --> 00:29:03,934
Oh, yes, yes. Andrea.

474
00:29:04,034 --> 00:29:06,645
Great Neck High School.
Likes Adele and Pinkberry.

475
00:29:06,745 --> 00:29:07,846
Yeah.

476
00:29:08,497 --> 00:29:09,439
I can come back.

477
00:29:09,539 --> 00:29:12,108
Oh, no, I think we're done.
Right? Are we done?

478
00:29:12,251 --> 00:29:13,523
Ten minutes ago.

479
00:29:15,879 --> 00:29:17,276
Nice to see you.

480
00:29:18,674 --> 00:29:19,783
Good morning.

481
00:29:19,883 --> 00:29:20,984
Uh...

482
00:29:22,135 --> 00:29:25,747
It could be said that we got off to a
poor start at the wine and cheese event.

483
00:29:25,847 --> 00:29:27,290
"We" did?

484
00:29:27,724 --> 00:29:28,959
